'''Sir Neville Noel Ashenheim''' (18 December 1900 – 1 September 1984) was a [[Jamaica]]n businessman, lawyer, politician, and served as the first Jamaican Ambassador to the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foer|first1=Paul|title=Jewish Jamaica, Then and Now|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2012/11/09/jewish-jamaica-then-and-now/|accessdate=11 March 2017|publisher=The Algemeiner|date=9 November 2012}}</ref>  He received a knighthood from [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 1 January 1963.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/42875/supplement/49/data.pdf|title=SIXTH SUPPLEMENT TO The London Gazette of Friday, 28th December 1962|last=|first=|date=1962-12-28|work=[[The London Gazette]]|access-date=}}</ref>  Ashenheim served his post as ambassador until March 1967.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} He was the great-grandson of Lewis Ashenheim, who coedited ''The First Fruits of the West'', the first Jewish [[Periodical literature|periodical]] in the [[West Indies]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7kiMNQ-O5_IC&pg=PA300&lpg=PA300&dq=neville+ashenheim+1963+knighthood&source=bl&ots=g7aEFm-9Mt&sig=IYMs0dUvwGgan-104PmC8Y_2Mp4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwij7MDO_9_cAhULV7wKHQMNC-0Q6AEwCXoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=neville%20ashenheim&f=false|title=Pioneer Jewish Texans|last=Ornish|first=Natalie|date=2011-09-01|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=2011|isbn=9781603444330|location=|pages=300|language=en}}</ref> Neville himself was a [[Jews|Jew]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=4iKxBYpK2CkC&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118&dq=%22Neville+Ashenheim%22&source=bl&ots=bBsLdTC3Th&sig=R0N5mPCuSw7M3QliB58sl8kwZdw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwivnu_4_d_cAhWBu7wKHcHMDyE4ChDoATAIegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22Neville%20Ashenheim%22&f=false|title=View from Mount Diablo: An Annotated Edition|last=Thompson|first=Ralph|last2=Lennard|first2=John|date=2009-01-01|publisher=Humanities-Ebooks|year=2009|isbn=9781847600936|location=|pages=118|language=en}}</ref>

