{{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = [[Seanad Éireann|Senator]] | name = Pádraig Ó Céidigh | image = | office = [[Seanad Éireann|Senator]] | term_start = 25 May 2016 | term_end = | constituency = [[Nominated members of Seanad Éireann|Nominated by the Taoiseach]] | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|1|2|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Connemara]], [[County Galway]], Ireland | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]] | party = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] | spouse = Caitlín Uí Chéidigh {{small|(m. 1983)}} | children = 4 | alma_mater = {{Ubl|[[NUI Galway]]|[[Harvard University]]}} | website = {{URL|padraigoceidigh.com}} |}} '''Pádraig Ó Céidigh''' ({{IPA-ga|ˈpˠaːd̪ˠɾˠəɟ oː ceːdʲiː|}}; born 1 February 1957<ref>http://www.aspire-wealth.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/20150503_Sunday_Times_Employing_a_top-notch_financial_adviser_is_money_well_spent.pdf</ref>) is an Irish [[Independent politician|Independent]] politician and redeveloper<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/aer-arann-families-annoyed-at-cidigh-37170454.html|title=Aer Arann families annoyed at Ó Céidigh|first=Kevin|last=Doyle|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=31 July 2018}}</ref> of Aer Arann Express and Aer Lingus Regional<ref name=personally/> who has served as a member of [[Seanad Éireann]] since May 2016, after being [[Nominated members of Seanad Éireann|nominated by the Taoiseach]].<ref name="appointment">{{cite web |archivedate=27 May 2016 |date=27 May 2016|accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0527/791478-seanad/ |publisher=[[RTÉ]] |title=Pieta House founder among Kenny's Seanad nominees|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527222035/http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0527/791478-seanad/ |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/search/?q=*:*&fq=nolc_keywords:%22Emer%20Ni%20Cheidigh%22|title=Search results for "*:*" - RTÉ Radio 1 |first=Strata3-|last=http://www.strata3.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.pictaural.ie/ihi/ihi003/speaker.php?id=s-PadraigOCeidigh |title=IHI: National Hospitality Managers' Conference & AGM A Gathering of Leaders|publisher=}}</ref>
He gained a [[Bachelor of Commerce|B.Comm.]] from [[NUI Galway|University College Galway]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite news|title=Class notes|work=Cois Coiribe|date=Autumn 2017|page=56}}</ref> He worked as an accountant and then as a teacher at [[Coláiste Iognáid]], went on to study law and began practicing with his own firm in the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nuigalway.ie/about-us/news-and-events/news-archive/2003/february2003/nui-galway-announces-awards-for-outstanding-graduates.html|title=NUI Galway announces Awards for Outstanding Graduates|date=3 February 2003}}</ref>
He ran unsuccessfully for one of the three Seanad seats allocated to the [[National University of Ireland (constituency)#2016 election|National University of Ireland]], losing on transfers despite being third on first preferences, but was nominated to the Seanad by the Taoiseach on 11 May 2016.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/taoiseachs-seanad-nominations-2791330-May2016/ Here's who the Taoiseach has chosen to fill the remaining Seanad seats] ''[[TheJournal.ie]]'', 26 May 2016.</ref>
Ó Céidigh served as a Member of the Governing Board of the Irish state broadcaster [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]]<ref name=personally>{{cite web|url=https://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/padraig/|title=Pádraig Ó Céidigh - Personally Speaking Bureau|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> prior to his appointment to Seanad Éireann.
In March 2018, he announced his intention to stand in the [[Irish presidential election, 2018|2018 presidential election]] against incumbent [[President of Ireland|President]] [[Michael D. Higgins]], as an Independent candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/padraig-o-ceidigh-is-fourth-senator-to-declare-intention-to-contest-presidency-s0zvt78zk|title=Pádraig Ó Céidigh is fourth senator to declare intention to contest presidency|first=Justine|last=McCarthy|authorlink=Justine McCarthy|date=2018-03-18|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-03-20|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>
